            <title>The top 10 signs that electric vehicles have gone mainstream</title>
            <description>&lt;p&gt;
	Electric vehicles have stormed into the American consciousness with news like the release of the Chevy Volt and the development of &lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/ge-unveils-residential-wattstation-ev-charger/" jquery1291384497270="8"&gt;home chargers&lt;/a&gt; fueling the EV enthusiasm. But have EVs thoroughly penetrated mainstream culture? Here are the 10 clearest signs that EVs have officially hit the big-time:&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	10. Leo&amp;rsquo;s got one. So do Matt Damon, Tom Hanks, and Bill Nye the Science Guy. &lt;a href="http://farm4.static.flickr.com/3261/2890118730_79672ff4e7.jpg?v=0" jquery1291384497270="9"&gt;Clooney&amp;rsquo;s even got 2 of them&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	9. Tokyo taxis are running on batteries that are switched out at stations in just 73 seconds (hard to believe? &lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/ge-better-place-to-partner-on-ev-infrastructure" jquery1291384497270="10"&gt;here&amp;rsquo;s the video&lt;/a&gt;). And &lt;a href="http://wheels.blogs.nytimes.com/2010/07/15/bloomberg-powers-up-new-electric-car-charging-program/" jquery1291384497270="11"&gt;NYC is powered up&lt;/a&gt; and ready to drive (emissions-free, that is).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	8. EVs are now the topic of pop songs&amp;hellip;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/top-10-signs-evs-have-gone-mainstream/?utm_source=feedburner&amp;amp;utm_medium=feed&amp;amp;utm_campaign=Feed%3A+gereports%2Ffeed+%28GE+Reports%29"&gt;http://www.gereports.com/top-10-signs-evs-have-gone-mainstream/?utm_source=feedburner&amp;amp;utm_medium=feed&amp;amp;utm_campaign=Feed%3A+gereports%2Ffeed+%28GE+Reports%29&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	7. &amp;hellip;Not to mention &lt;a href="http://www.engadget.com/2010/06/30/dippin-in-my-tesla-is-the-best-rap-song-ever-about-a-tesla/" jquery1291384497270="12"&gt;rap songs&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	6. Jeff Immelt is planning to buy &lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/in-largest-single-commitment-ge-to-buy-25000-electric-vehicles/" jquery1291384497270="13"&gt;25,000&lt;/a&gt; of them.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	5. &lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/the-10-best-cities-for-electric-cars/" jquery1291384497270="14"&gt;Big cities&lt;/a&gt; around the country are ready for them.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	4. They&amp;rsquo;ve even become the &lt;a href="http://www.revengeoftheelectriccar.com/" jquery1291384497270="15"&gt;stars of movies&lt;/a&gt;!&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	3. On &lt;a href="http://www.facebook.com/gmchevyvolt" jquery1291384497270="16"&gt;Facebook&lt;/a&gt;, more people &amp;ldquo;like&amp;rdquo; the Chevy Volt than &amp;ldquo;like&amp;rdquo; you&amp;hellip;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	2. They&amp;rsquo;re not just about being good for the environment &amp;mdash; one EV (the &lt;a href="http://www.teslamotors.com/roadster" jquery1291384497270="17"&gt;Tesla Roadster&lt;/a&gt;) accelerates &lt;a href="http://www.scientificamerican.com/blog/post.cfm?id=the-tesla-roadster-is-a-rocket-and-2009-09-28" jquery1291384497270="18"&gt;faster than a Porsche, a Corvette, and a Ferrari&lt;/a&gt;.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	1.They&amp;rsquo;re winning awards: &lt;em&gt;Motor Trend&lt;/em&gt; named the Chevy Volt its &lt;a href="http://www.motortrend.com/oftheyear/car/1101_2011_motor_trend_car_of_the_year_chevrolet_volt/index.html" jquery1291384497270="19"&gt;2011 Car of the Year&lt;/a&gt;, and the Nissan Leaf beat 40 other vehicles to be named &lt;a href="http://www.wired.com/autopia/2010/11/nissan-leaf-wins-europes-car-of-the-year/" jquery1291384497270="20"&gt;Europe&amp;rsquo;s 2011 &amp;ldquo;car of the year.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;div class="large_img_wtext" sizcache="3" sizset="1"&gt;
	&lt;p sizcache="3" sizset="1"&gt;
		&lt;img alt="" src="http://files.gereports.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/12/tesla.jpg" /&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
	&lt;p&gt;
		&lt;span&gt;In a flash:&lt;/span&gt; &lt;em&gt;Scientific American&lt;/em&gt; calls the sports edition of the Tesla Roadster &amp;ldquo;blistering fast&amp;rdquo; &amp;mdash; it can go from zero to 60 miles per hour in 3.7 seconds. Photo: Tesla.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;/div&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	* Take a look at &lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/driving-down-ev-memory-lane-a-look-back-at-ges-test-models/" jquery1291384497270="21"&gt;GE&amp;rsquo;s other EV research over the years&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
	* Read &lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/dual-battery-breakthrough-eyes-electric-bus-truck-fleets" jquery1291384497270="22"&gt;&amp;ldquo;Dual Battery Breakthrough Eyes Electric Bus and Truck Fleets&amp;rdquo;&lt;/a&gt;&lt;br /&gt;
	* See our infographic on the &lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/the-10-best-cities-for-electric-cars/" jquery1291384497270="23"&gt;10 Best Cities for Electric Vehicles&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/noria/reliableplant/tags/energy_management/~4/dvNffBBXyfk" height="1" width="1" alt=""/&gt;</description>
