            <title>Toro partners with ATK to develop fuel cell-powered utility vehicles</title>
            <description>&lt;p&gt;
	The Toro Company was selected by ATK, an aerospace and defense company, to help design and build two fuel cell powered utility vehicles with advanced hydrogen storage technology. The project is part of a contract awarded to ATK by the Naval Surface Warfare Center Crane Division, which is collaborating with the Defense Logistics Agency (DLA) to coordinate hydrogen storage development efforts for the U.S. Department of Energy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	As partner in the project, Toro provides extensive operational experience in the area of fuel cell technologies having recently completed a three-year demonstration with the New York State Energy Research and Development Authority (NYSERDA). The NYSERDA project used three prototype hydrogen-powered Toro Workman utility vehicles at various sites, including Niagara Falls State Park, Bethpage State Park and Rockefeller Plaza Government Center. These vehicles operated reliably in shuttling workers and grounds equipment, hauling turf materials, and assisting with refuse removal. The demonstration proved fuel cells technically viable and feedback from operators was consistently positive.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	With proven experience in mobile fuel cell technology and off-road utility vehicle application, Toro caught the attention of ATK&amp;rsquo;s Center for Energy and Aerospace Innovation (CEAI), based in Ronkonkoma, New York. Toro&amp;rsquo;s Center for Advanced Turf Technology (CATT) will assist in designing two operational machines based on the Toro Workman chassis and similar to what the company successfully demonstrated in New York. The group will also provide technical expertise on end-use applications.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&amp;ldquo;We&amp;rsquo;re excited to partner on this project to leverage our field experience and further our efforts in the development of alternative fuel solutions,&amp;rdquo; said Dana Lonn, director of Toro&amp;rsquo;s CATT Group. &amp;ldquo;Our motivation in alternative energy is to reduce emissions, hydraulic leaks and noise levels for our customers. Therefore, we need to remain aggressive in identifying the best technologies to deliver these results at a competitive price.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The fuel cell utility vehicles, powered by a solid hydrogen storage system, are scheduled for delivery later this fall to the DLA for a 12-month operational demonstration. During this time, the vehicles will retrieve and transport materials between warehouses with data being collected to better understand the performance, durability and sustainability of the hydrogen fuel cell system.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Shaped by concerns over energy usage and the environment, the Energy Policy Act of 2005 requires that the U.S. Department of Defense reduce oil consumption rates by 20 percent before the end of 2015. The energy law also establishes a hydrogen and fuel cell program with a goal of producing commercial fuel cell vehicles and developing hydrogen infrastructure by 2020.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/noria/reliableplant/tags/energy_management/~4/3hRA3_iPK8c" height="1" width="1" alt=""/&gt;</description>
            <a10:updated>2010-11-01T07:54:57-05:00</a10:updated>
            <a10:content type="text/html" src="http://reliableplant.com/Read/27230/Toro-ATK-electric-vehicles" />
        <feedburner:origLink>http://reliableplant.com/Read/27230/Toro-ATK-electric-vehicles</feedburner:origLink></item>
        <item>
            <guid isPermaLink="false">tag:noria.com,2010-06-10:publishing:magazines:rp:8dcb691d-a713-4464-8758-9e2100760731</guid>
            <link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/noria/reliableplant/tags/energy_management/~3/OX5tDqTpwWc/Electric-vehicles-smarter-grid</link>
            <a10:author>
                <a10:name>General Electric</a10:name>
            </a10:author>
            <category>Industry News</category>
            <category>Articles</category>
            <title>Why electric vehicles need a smarter grid</title>
            <description>&lt;p&gt;
	With electric vehicle adoption by consumers heading toward a tipping point, utilities and cities are busy planning just how to meet the power demands of millions of EVs. &lt;a href="http://www.forbes.com/2010/10/29/smart-grid-recharging-technology-electric-vehicles.html?boxes=techchanneltopstories" jquery1288613197367="8"&gt;In an essay published today in &lt;em&gt;Forbes&lt;/em&gt;,&lt;/a&gt; GE&amp;rsquo;s Bob Gilligan, who is the vice president for GE&amp;rsquo;s digital energy business, makes the case that the environmental and economical benefits of EVs will be stunted if their cords don&amp;rsquo;t plug into a smarter grid.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&amp;nbsp;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table sizcache="0" sizset="1" style="border-bottom: #cccccc 1px solid; border-left: #cccccc 1px solid; width: 500px; font-family: arial; margin-bottom: 10px; border-top: #cccccc 1px solid; margin-right: 16px; border-right: #cccccc 1px solid"&gt;
	&lt;tbody sizcache="0" sizset="1"&gt;
		&lt;tr sizcache="0" sizset="1"&gt;
			&lt;td sizcache="0" sizset="1" style="padding-bottom: 9px; padding-left: 9px; padding-right: 9px; font-size: 8pt; padding-top: 9px"&gt;
				&lt;img alt="" border="0" src="http://files.gereports.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/wattstation-home.jpg" style="margin-bottom: 1em" /&gt;&lt;span style="font-size: 8pt; font-weight: bold"&gt;Grid ready:&lt;/span&gt; EV chargers like &lt;a href="http://www.geindustrial.com/products/static/WattStation/" jquery1288613197367="9"&gt;GE&amp;rsquo;s WattStation&lt;/a&gt; feature smart grid connections and faster refueling times.&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	With charging infrastructure still in the early development phase, &amp;ldquo;the novelty of a few electric cars can be absorbed by the current power system,&amp;rdquo; he writes. &amp;ldquo;But as more EVs replace regular cars, they could overtax the current power grid if they aren&amp;rsquo;t charged at off-peak times.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&amp;ldquo;During peak periods &amp;mdash; the time of greatest power demand &amp;mdash; utilities are forced to activate additional, more expensive &amp;lsquo;peaker plants&amp;rsquo; to meet spikes in energy demand. Those increased operating costs translate into higher consumption costs for consumers. Which means it&amp;rsquo;s more economical for EV drivers to recharge when the power is &amp;lsquo;on sale&amp;rsquo; during off-peak periods.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	As Bob explains, the national EV infrastructure envisioned by industry players is more than just chargers in home garages. Rather, it&amp;rsquo;s nothing short of &amp;ldquo;electrified versions of gas pumps&amp;rdquo; that will be needed. He says that &amp;ldquo;by 2015 there will be an estimated 3 million EV charging stations installed worldwide; this year, a mere 20,000 installations are forecast.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The net takeaway, Bob writes, is that the grid needs to be upgraded to support the new EV world. Not doing it will also &amp;ldquo;keep some consumers away until a comprehensive infrastructure is in place.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	To make this happen, he says, partnerships need to be forged to develop technology standards so utilities and tech companies can be on the same page and know how to invest. On the consumer side, increased awareness about exactly what a smart grid is &amp;ndash; and how it&amp;rsquo;s needed for EVs, needs to happen at the same time. &amp;ldquo;Only then will we get the most out of an electrified transportation network,&amp;rdquo; he writes.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Learn more in these GE Reports stories:&lt;br /&gt;
	* &amp;ldquo;&lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/will-the-cost-of-electric-cars-come-down-we-asked-a123/" jquery1288613197367="10"&gt;Will the Cost of Electric Cars Come Down? We Asked A123&lt;/a&gt;&amp;rdquo;&lt;br /&gt;
	* &amp;ldquo;&lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/drive-an-ev-slash-the-co2/" jquery1288613197367="11"&gt;Drive an EV, Slash the CO2&lt;/a&gt;&amp;rdquo;&lt;br /&gt;
	* &amp;ldquo;&lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/how-far-will-your-ev-go-it-depends-how-fast-you-charge-it/" jquery1288613197367="12"&gt;How Far Will Your EV Go? It Depends How Fast You Charge It&lt;/a&gt;&amp;rdquo;&lt;br /&gt;
	* &amp;ldquo;&lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/the-real-state-of-electric-vehicles-in-a-billion-car-world/" jquery1288613197367="13"&gt;The Real State of Electric Vehicles in a Billion-Car World&lt;/a&gt;&amp;rdquo;&lt;br /&gt;
	* &amp;ldquo;&lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/ge-unveils-residential-wattstation-ev-charger/" jquery1288613197367="14"&gt;GE unveils residential WattStation EV charger&lt;/a&gt;&amp;rdquo;&lt;br /&gt;
	* &amp;ldquo;&lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/ge-better-place-to-partner-on-ev-infrastructure/" jquery1288613197367="15"&gt;GE &amp;amp; Better Place to partner on EV infrastructure&lt;/a&gt;&amp;rdquo;&lt;br /&gt;
	* &amp;ldquo;&lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/ge-teams-with-nissan-on-electric-car-smart-charging/" jquery1288613197367="16"&gt;GE teams with Nissan on electric car smart charging&lt;/a&gt;&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/noria/reliableplant/tags/energy_management/~4/OX5tDqTpwWc" height="1" width="1" alt=""/&gt;</description>
