                <a10:name>RP news wires</a10:name>
            </a10:author>
            <category>Industry News</category>
            <category>Articles</category>
            <title>Butterball selects EPS to increase energy efficiency</title>
            <description>&lt;p&gt;
	EPS Corp on October 20 announced that Butterball, LLC, the largest producer of turkey products in the United States, has selected EPS&amp;rsquo; xChange Point real-time energy management and carbon reduction solution as a technology enabler to achieve its energy efficiency and sustainability goals. xChange Point will initially be deployed at Butterball&amp;rsquo;s manufacturing facility in Mt. Olive, N.C., to analyze current energy consumption and carbon emissions, identify areas for the greatest improvement, and design a strategy to increase overall plant energy efficiency.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	One of the key elements in Butterball&amp;rsquo;s Corporate Social Responsibility directive, &amp;ldquo;sustainability&amp;rdquo; is a top priority for the corporation. For that reason, Butterball wanted to add an energy intelligence system that would allow the company to monitor and reduce their energy use and carbon emissions and achieve their overall sustainability targets. Butterball selected EPS Corp because of the company&amp;rsquo;s expertise in industrial energy efficiency and the breadth of its real-time xChange Point energy management solution, backed by a team of energy analysts and engineers to recommend and implement the most effective sustainability initiatives in concert with Butterball&amp;rsquo;s internal team.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&amp;ldquo;Butterball is dedicated to being a good steward of the environment,&amp;rdquo; said Steve Valesko, vice president of engineering for Butterball LLC. &amp;ldquo;The EPS system provides our company with real-time measurements for obtaining our sustainability goals, resulting in cost reductions for the facilities as well as reinforcing our commitment to the environmental community.&amp;rdquo;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	EPS&amp;rsquo; xChange Point system is deployed by multiple Fortune 1000 manufacturing companies to use real- time, enterprise-wide data, together with recommendations by EPS experts, to reduce energy and water use and carbon emissions. This software as a service solution provides an enterprise-wide view of important sustainability and production metrics that can help reduce costs while improving sustainability at facilities across the enterprise &amp;ndash; making it a powerful solution for leading global companies such as Butterball to understand their energy, water, and carbon profiles.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/noria/reliableplant/tags/energy_management/~4/MEsDIpCRl5c" height="1" width="1" alt=""/&gt;</description>
            <a10:updated>2010-10-20T14:30:42-05:00</a10:updated>
            <a10:content type="text/html" src="http://reliableplant.com/Read/27059/Butterball-EPS-energy-efficiency" />
        <feedburner:origLink>http://reliableplant.com/Read/27059/Butterball-EPS-energy-efficiency</feedburner:origLink></item>
        <item>
            <guid isPermaLink="false">tag:noria.com,2010-06-10:publishing:magazines:rp:89afc3b1-bd99-4b49-933c-9e1500eb2cea</guid>
            <link>http://feedproxy.google.com/~r/noria/reliableplant/tags/energy_management/~3/K9Qt7vos1zA/GE-technologies-waste-energy</link>
            <a10:author>
                <a10:name>General Electric</a10:name>
            </a10:author>
            <category>Industry News</category>
            <category>Articles</category>
            <title>The top five GE technologies that turn waste into energy</title>
            <description>&lt;p&gt;
	Here is a list of the top five GE technologies that turn waste into energy.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;strong&gt;1. The Nuclear Reactor That Eats Its Own Waste &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table sizcache="0" sizset="1" style="border-bottom: #cccccc 1px solid; border-left: #cccccc 1px solid; width: 500px; font-family: arial; margin-bottom: 10px; border-top: #cccccc 1px solid; margin-right: 16px; border-right: #cccccc 1px solid"&gt;
	&lt;tbody sizcache="0" sizset="1"&gt;
		&lt;tr sizcache="0" sizset="1"&gt;
			&lt;td sizcache="0" sizset="1" style="padding-bottom: 9px; padding-left: 9px; padding-right: 9px; font-size: 8pt; padding-top: 9px"&gt;
				&lt;img alt="" border="0" src="http://files.gereports.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/prism_both_cutaway.jpg" style="margin-bottom: 1em" /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/an-update-on-the-nuclear-reactor-that-eats-its-own-waste/"&gt;GE&amp;rsquo;s Hitachi Advanced Recycling Center&lt;/a&gt; burns nuclear waste (even weapons-grade plutonium), and emits zero CO2.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Here&amp;rsquo;s the secret: The system uses sodium to control the nuclear reaction, instead of high-pressure water. Sodium-cooling allows the reactor to &amp;ldquo;burn&amp;rdquo; the leftover energy in used fuel. When used fuel is removed from a traditional water-cooled reactor, 95 percent of its potential energy is still untapped.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;strong&gt;2. The Jenbacher Engine&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table sizcache="0" sizset="2" style="border-bottom: #cccccc 1px solid; border-left: #cccccc 1px solid; width: 500px; font-family: arial; margin-bottom: 10px; border-top: #cccccc 1px solid; margin-right: 16px; border-right: #cccccc 1px solid"&gt;
	&lt;tbody sizcache="0" sizset="2"&gt;
		&lt;tr sizcache="0" sizset="2"&gt;
			&lt;td sizcache="0" sizset="2" style="padding-bottom: 9px; padding-left: 9px; padding-right: 9px; font-size: 8pt; padding-top: 9px"&gt;
				&lt;img alt="" border="0" src="http://files.gereports.com/wp-content/uploads/2009/09/china_jenbacher.jpg" style="margin-bottom: 1em" /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/ges-new-michigan-tech-center-revs-up-with-landfill-gas/" jquery1287602047168="8"&gt;The Jenbacher could be called the alchemist of energy&lt;/a&gt;: It&amp;rsquo;s a gas-fueled reciprocating engine that can run on natural gas, biogas, landfill gas, coal mine gas, sewage gas, and more.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	Jenbachers are used by a broad range of commercial, industrial, and municipal customers to generate power, heat, and cooling. Europe currently has more than 1,100 engines running on biogas, and they&amp;rsquo;re being used to convert coal mine gas to electricity in Australia and Ukraine. (&lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/ge-powers-chinas-largest-chicken-waste-biogas-plant/" jquery1287602047168="9"&gt;China&amp;rsquo;s largest chicken waste biogas plant&lt;/a&gt; is seen above).&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;strong&gt;3. The Hybrid Locomotive &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table sizcache="0" sizset="3" style="border-bottom: #cccccc 1px solid; border-left: #cccccc 1px solid; width: 500px; font-family: arial; margin-bottom: 10px; border-top: #cccccc 1px solid; margin-right: 16px; border-right: #cccccc 1px solid"&gt;
	&lt;tbody sizcache="0" sizset="3"&gt;
		&lt;tr sizcache="0" sizset="3"&gt;
			&lt;td sizcache="0" sizset="3" style="padding-bottom: 9px; padding-left: 9px; padding-right: 9px; font-size: 8pt; padding-top: 9px"&gt;
				&lt;img alt="" border="0" src="http://files.gereports.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/eco-locomotive.jpg" style="margin-bottom: 1em" /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;a href="http://www.ecomagination.com/technologies/evolution-hybrid-locomotive/" jquery1287602047168="10"&gt;The Evolution Hybrid Locomotive&lt;/a&gt; can capture and store braking energy for later use. Every time the conductor hits the brakes, ordinarily wasted braking energy goes to fueling the battery.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	The energy that&amp;rsquo;s wasted in braking a 207-ton locomotive during the course of one year is enough to power over 8,900 average U.S. households for a year.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;strong&gt;4. Waste Heat Recovery&lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table sizcache="0" sizset="4" style="border-bottom: #cccccc 1px solid; border-left: #cccccc 1px solid; width: 500px; font-family: arial; margin-bottom: 10px; border-top: #cccccc 1px solid; margin-right: 16px; border-right: #cccccc 1px solid"&gt;
	&lt;tbody sizcache="0" sizset="4"&gt;
		&lt;tr sizcache="0" sizset="4"&gt;
			&lt;td sizcache="0" sizset="4" style="padding-bottom: 9px; padding-left: 9px; padding-right: 9px; font-size: 8pt; padding-top: 9px"&gt;
				&lt;img alt="" border="0" src="http://files.gereports.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/10/calnetixps_image_lg.jpg" style="margin-bottom: 1em" /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/ge-enters-1b-waste-heat-recovery-sector-with-calnetix-acquisition/" jquery1287602047168="11"&gt;The technology GE just acquired from Calnetix&lt;/a&gt; recovers heat given off by industrial processes and uses it to produce electricity. It&amp;rsquo;s a fast-growing trend in the global power industry, and for good reason: it can dramatically improve operating efficiency while lowering a carbon footprint.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	How it works: heat is captured in an evaporator that boils the working fluid, producing vapor. The vapor expands, spinning a turbine, which drives a generator and produces electricity. The vapor is then cooled back to a liquid and pumped back to the evaporator to repeat the process.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;strong&gt;5. Re-Using Industrial Wastewater So There&amp;rsquo;s More For Your Tap &lt;/strong&gt;&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;table sizcache="0" sizset="5" style="border-bottom: #cccccc 1px solid; border-left: #cccccc 1px solid; width: 500px; font-family: arial; margin-bottom: 10px; border-top: #cccccc 1px solid; margin-right: 16px; border-right: #cccccc 1px solid"&gt;
	&lt;tbody sizcache="0" sizset="5"&gt;
		&lt;tr sizcache="0" sizset="5"&gt;
			&lt;td sizcache="0" sizset="5" style="padding-bottom: 9px; padding-left: 9px; padding-right: 9px; font-size: 8pt; padding-top: 9px"&gt;
				&lt;img alt="" border="0" src="http://files.gereports.com/wp-content/uploads/2010/08/True-Sense-PWA-Lab2.jpg" style="margin-bottom: 1em" /&gt;&lt;/td&gt;
		&lt;/tr&gt;
	&lt;/tbody&gt;
&lt;/table&gt;
&lt;p&gt;
	&lt;a href="http://www.gereports.com/well-drink-to-that-new-tech-to-boost-water-re-use/" jquery1287602047168="12"&gt;Twenty percent of all water consumed is used for industrial purposes&lt;/a&gt; &amp;mdash; a medium-sized industrial cooling tower sucks up 1.5 million gallons of fresh water each day. GE&amp;rsquo;s TrueSense technology can slash this fresh water use by up to 20% and save $400,000 annually &amp;mdash; with part of the system using an iPad-sized monitoring system and a set of diagnostic tools. By industries using less water in the first place, there&amp;rsquo;s more freshwater available for the drinking water that energizes you.&lt;/p&gt;&lt;img src="http://feeds.feedburner.com/~r/noria/reliableplant/tags/energy_management/~4/K9Qt7vos1zA" height="1" width="1" alt=""/&gt;</description>
            <a10:updated>2010-10-20T14:16:12-05:00</a10:updated>
            <a10:content type="text/html" src="http://reliableplant.com/Read/27056/GE-technologies-waste-energy" />
